values:
Since no one really updates this or reads it anymore, I am going to start posting on Myspace instead. It will be easier to only have to check one website and everyone that has ever commented on my livejournal is on myspace as well. Anyone who might read this, but not comment on it, my profile on myspace.com is 
http://www.myspace.com/philipvogelsberg

The link directly to my weblog is
http://blog.myspace.com/philipvogelsberg

So goodbye livejournal! Its been fun, but its easier to put pictures and other stuff on myspace.

For some reason lately the small talk has been harder than ever.  I go to work and see these guys who I see every day and have almost nothing in common with and struggle to think of anything to say.  I am not even worried about trying to say something funny or amusing or clever; just trying to think of ANYTHING worth saying is hard.  I think its worse now that I have been thinking about it because if there is anything that makes pointless small talk even worse, its being under pressure to have something to say.  Like today for example.  Chris (a guy I work with) and I had lunch with two vendors for a company that sell products that we are using.  So for a full hour we have to make conversation with these guys who are both at least 20 years older then us about football, air conditioning, housing, and a slew of other interesting and stimulating topics.  It is so weird that if it gets quiet, it has to feel awkward.  Like I am not a very interesting or social person or something.  There are so many people out there who can just sit down and talk to anyone at any time and be laughing and interesting the whole time.  And you know that those salesmen (and everyone else) greatly prefers the company of those people to dorks like me.  Its so weird because when I am around people who have shared interests, I talk quite a bit.  A good example is Dave from my last job.  I used to love talking to him about movies, music, food, and things that I find interesting.  Maybe I just need to take up some totally lame, but socially accepted (at least in Texas) hobbies like fishing or hunting or driving sports cars or playing poker three times a week.

I drove to work this morning and just as I was about to get out of my car, I heard a familiar beat. I was mesmorized and unable to get out of the car, no matter how I tried to resist.  It was "Chewing Gum" by Annie!!  I could not believe it!  I had heard a song by her on the radio before, but never THAT song.  It was ridiculous.  That's the beauty of XM radio, you get to hear the stuff they just don't play anywhere else.  Except for on Fred's computer, that is.  Needless to say, the rest of my morning was spent with "Oh no. Oh no. You've got it all wrong." endlessly going through my head.  Unfortunately, that was the highlight of my morning.  I had cement class all day and it was sooo boring.  I am more than ready to get back to my regular job.  All these classes make me feel like I am back at school.  At least I am getting a paycheck so I can't really complain.  I will do whatever the hell they want me to do for 40 hours a week.  I really shouldn't complain... there are far worse things to be doing all day than sitting in a class room.  I look out the windows and see the construction workers busting there asses in the 90 degree sun all day and thank the Lord I went to school.

I am leaving in a few hours for the first leg of my five-week training course.  This is the team-building portion and I have no idea what to expect. There are 24 people from the US, Scotland, and The Netherlands that will be participating.  I will be back in Houston on Tuesday night for the second part of the course.  And of course right before I go on a training thing where I have to meet 23 new people that I will be seeing and workig with regularly for 5 weeks and try to make friends, I have a big, under-the-skin pimple on the side of my forehead! Well, at least its not on my nose or my chin. So wish me luck and I will let everyone know how it went when I get back on Tuesday.

You know how when something bad happens out of the blue, it is much worse then if you knew it was going to happen and could prepare for it? For example, I am leaving on my training tomorrow and I think the fact that we have known about it for a long time and have been talking about it will make it much better than if we just woke up tomorrow morning and I found out that I had to leave that same day.  I was just thinking that the same principle applies to having fun.  It seems like the most fun times are always the ones that happen unexpectedly.  We were talking the other day about how when you are really looking forward to something, it is never as good.  I think the best kind of fun is the unexpected kind, just like the worst kind of trouble is the unexpected kind.  You might argue that knowing something bad is coming makes you apprehensive and hence causes more unhappiness in the worrying than the actual event.  While this may be true for some people, I still think that when the event actually happens, it will be less bad if you are prepared for it.  I think the same holds true for enjoying something.  You may get a lot of enjoyment out of looking forward to something, but it saps the enjoyment you would get out of it if it were a surprise.

Quote of the Day:
Some people walk in the rain, others just get wet.  ~Roger Miller

Phil's Top 3 Favorite Ice Cream Flavors:

  1. Ben and Jerry's "Everything But The..." (so many tasty things in here, it is the absolute best)
  2. Mint Chocolate Chip  (my childhood favorite)
  3. Cookies and Cream  (yum. what else can I say?)

I would just like to give a quick explanation as to why I prefer music to movies.  I know most of you out there are movie fans, so feel free to call me a dumbass in the comments section.  One of the biggest reasons is that in most movies, everything is so spelled out for you that it takes absolutely no thought to follow or comprehend.  There are exceptions, obviously, but I just mean your typical Hollywood movie.  I feel like a really good album lets the listener interpret the songs in a way that is very personal and distinct for that individual.  Also, I feel like I get a lot more replay value out of my albums.  Usually, I only like to watch a movie once.  If its one that I really like, I will enjoy seeing it more times, but not more often than once every couple months at the most.  When it comes to music, however, there are albums that I have listened to over and over throughout the years until I knew every single lyric.  Plus, listening to music does not take up all of your concentration like a movie.  You can listen to good music in the car, at work, while talking to friends, or while I write my live journal.  Obviously, there are tons of great movies out there that I really like, I am just explaining why I purchase CDs, but am content to rent 90% of the movies I see. There are some that I would like to own and do own, but my music is much more important to me.  By its very nature, music is more honest than movies.  Movies are people acting emotional for the camera, whereas a good artist will be inspired to play and sing by his/her strongest emotions.  Usually, the best way to generate emotion on the screen is through using music.

Quote of the Day:

Music expresses that which cannot be said and on which it is impossible to be silent.  ~Victor Hugo

Phils Top 3 Favorite Dr. Pepper Imitations:

  1. Mr. Green (The packaging looks so stupid that I didn't want to try it, but the taste is top-notch.)
  2. Mr. Pibb (WAAAAY better than Pibb Extra. Pibb Extra should have been called Pibb Smooth or Pibb Less because it has way less bite than the original.)
  3. Cherry Vanilla Dr. Pepper (Not really an immitation, but it sure is tasty.)

Ones I have tried that are not as good : Dr. M, Dr. K, Dr. Becker, Dr. Shasta, Dr Soda, Dr. Thunder, Pibb Extra, Dr. West, Dr. Skipper, and others.  Its sad that my favorite two have both been discontinued.
"Farts are fun. Its shit without the mess." ~ George Carlin
It is better to fail in originality than to succeed in imitation.  ~Herman Melville
